	heroObjectPosition={`center 30%`}
	directAnswerHtml={`<strong style="color: var(--color-ink);">If you have lost your spouse, the Father's Heart Bible™ is for you.</strong> Bible verses for widows — and for widowers — are not distant comfort; they are the voice of a God who names Himself "Father of the fatherless and protector of widows" (Psalm 68:5). The <a href="https://fathersheartbible.com/read" style="color: var(--color-brand);" class="hover:underline">Father's Heart Bible™</a> is a fresh English translation you can read and <em>listen to</em> free on your phone — and it reveals God as a <em>Father</em> from beginning to end. Whether you searched "Bible verses for widows," "comfort after losing a spouse," or "does God care for widows" — the answer begins here: He sees the chair no one fills, He keeps every tear, and He has not forgotten you.`}
	keyTakeaway={`Scripture gives the widow and widower a specific promise: God Himself is your defender and provider. In a season when you feel most alone and unseen, your Father draws nearest — close to the brokenhearted, attentive to the lonely, faithful when everything familiar is gone.`}
	painsHeading={`The weight widows and widowers carry`}
	painsIntroHtml={`If you feel unmoored, anxious about the future, or achingly alone, you are not failing at grief and you are not alone in it. Across this country, millions are walking the same road — and the numbers name a sorrow that often goes unspoken.`}
	painStats={[
		{ value: `~15M`, label: `U.S. adults are widowed — about 6% of the adult population (U.S. Census Bureau)` },
		{ value: `80%`, label: `of widowed Americans are women; widows outnumber widowers more than 4 to 1 (U.S. Census Bureau)` },
		{ value: `~59`, label: `is the median age a woman is first widowed — and 1 in 3 are widowed before 60 (U.S. Census Bureau)` },
		{ value: `~40%`, label: `average drop in household income after a spouse dies (Consumer Financial Protection Bureau)` },
		{ value: `15.5%`, label: `of widows age 65+ live below the poverty line, versus 5.8% of married women (CRS / Census, 2021)` },
		{ value: `15 yrs`, label: `Half of widows over 65 will outlive their spouse by 15 years or more — long years of adjusting to life alone (U.S. Census Bureau)` },
	]}
	painsBodyHtml={`<p>Behind every number is a name, a marriage, a life that was shared and is now carried alone. The morning you reach for someone who isn't there. The decisions you used to make together and now face by yourself. The well-meaning friends whose calls slowly taper off while the loneliness only deepens. The fear about money, about the house, about growing old without your person beside you.</p><p>This is not weakness, and it is not a lack of faith. It is love with nowhere to land. And into exactly this place — the silent house, the long evening, the unspoken ache — there is a Father who steps close, not with a lecture, but with His presence. He has a great deal to say to the widow and the widower, and almost all of it is tender.</p>`}
	painsSources={[
		{ label: `U.S. Census Bureau — Marriage, Divorce, Widowhood Remain Prevalent Among Older Populations`, url: `https://www.census.gov/library/stories/2021/04/love-and-loss-among-older-adults.html` },
		{ label: `Congressional Research Service — Poverty Among the Population Aged 65 and Older`, url: `https://www.congress.gov/crs-product/R45791` },
		{ label: `Consumer Financial Protection Bureau — Financial Challenges Faced by Recently Widowed Older Adults`, url: `https://www.consumerfinance.gov/data-research/research-reports/data-spotlight-financial-challenges-faced-by-recently-widowed-older-adults/full-report/` },
	]}
	aFatherHeading={`A Father for widows and widowers`}
	aFatherBodyHtml={`<p>There is a verse that most people read past, but that the grieving heart should never miss. It says God is the "<strong style="color: var(--color-ink);">Father of the fatherless and protector of widows</strong>" (Psalm 68:5). Of all the ways the infinite God could introduce Himself, He chose this: the One who stands up for the person who has lost their covering. That is not poetry. That is a promise with your name on it.</p><p>When your spouse died, you did not lose your place in His heart — you moved closer to its center. Scripture says He is near to the brokenhearted, that He sets the lonely in families, that He keeps count of your tossing and stores every tear in His bottle. He notices the empty side of the bed. He hears the prayers you only half know how to pray.</p><p>And to the widow especially, He says something staggering through the prophet Isaiah: "Your Maker is your husband." The God who made you promises to be the covering, the provider, the steady presence you have lost. You are not on your own. You have a Father — and He has not forgotten you.</p>`}
